406→                           In <a href="#cite-Er46b-223" onclick="event.preventDefault();addNewBox('Er46b','223'); return false;">[Er46b]</a> Erdős says this was a conjecture of Vázsonyi.<ul>
407→<li>Hopf and Pannwitz <a href="#cite-HoPa34-223" onclick="event.preventDefault();addNewBox('HoPa34','223'); return false;">[HoPa34]</a> proved $f_2(n)=n$ (with an elegant simple proof described by Erdős in <a href="#cite-Er46b-223" onclick="event.preventDefault();addNewBox('Er46b','223'); return false;">[Er46b]</a>).</li>
408→<li>Grünbaum <a href="#cite-Gr56-223" onclick="event.preventDefault();addNewBox('Gr56','223'); return false;">[Gr56]</a>, Heppes <a href="#cite-He56-223" onclick="event.preventDefault();addNewBox('He56','223'); return false;">[He56]</a>, and Strasziewicz <a href="#cite-St57-223" onclick="event.preventDefault();addNewBox('St57','223'); return false;">[St57]</a> independently showed that $f_3(n)=2n-2$.</li>
409→<li>Erdős <a href="#cite-Er60b-223" onclick="event.preventDefault();addNewBox('Er60b','223'); return false;">[Er60b]</a> proved that, for $d\geq 4$, $f_d(n)=(\frac{p-1}{2p}+o(1))n^2$ where $p=\lfloor d/2\rfloor$.</li>
410→<li>Swanepoel <a href="#cite-Sw09-223" onclick="event.preventDefault();addNewBox('Sw09','223'); return false;">[Sw09]</a> gave, for all $d\geq 4$, an exact description of $f_d(n)$ for all $n$ sufficiently large depending on $d$, and also gave the extremal configurations.</li>
411→</ul>See also <a href="/132" rel="nofollow noopener noreferrer ugc" target="_blank">[132]</a>, and <a href="/1084" rel="nofollow noopener noreferrer ugc" target="_blank">[1084]</a> for the analogous problem with minimal distance $1$.
